According to the [[Office for National Statistics]], at the time of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], Radcliffe had a population of&nbsp;34,239.  The population density in 2001 was {{convert|9132|PD/sqmi|0}}, with a 100&nbsp;to&nbsp;94.9&nbsp;female<U+2013>male ratio.<ref>{{Citation | title = KS01 Usual resident population: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas | publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8271&More=Y |date=2005-02-07 | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref> Of those over 16&nbsp;years old, 28.6% were single (never married) and 42.8% married.<ref>{{Citation |title=KS04 Marital status: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8276&More=Y |date=2005-02-02 | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref>  Radcliffe's 14,036&nbsp;households included 28.1% one-person, 39.0% married couples living together, 9.2% were co-habiting couples, and 12.3% single parents with their children.<ref>{{Citation |title=KS20 Household composition: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8349&More=Y |date=2005-02-02 | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref>  The figures for married couples households was below the borough (48.5%) and national average (47.3%), and single parent households were slightly above the average for the whole of Bury (11.6%) and England (10.5%).<ref>{{Citation |title=Area: Bury (Local Authority): Household type |publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=276777&c=bury&d=13&e=16&g=350821&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1225320045820&enc=1&dsFamilyId=171 | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref>  Of those aged 16<U+2013>74, 31.1% had no academic qualifications, slightly higher than averages of Bury (29.2%) and England (28.9%).<ref name="Bury neighbourhood stats"/><ref>{{Citation |title=KS13 Qualifications and students: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas |publisher=Statistics.gov.uk |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8326&More=Y| date=2005-02-02 | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref>

The residential areas of Radcliffe both to the north and the south of the town centre operate as suburbs of Bury and Manchester, such that their populations are not necessarily linked to the town.  The socio-demographic characteristics of the town's population includes a mix of working and suburban middle classes, the layout of which are both linked to neighbouring towns.<ref name="renaissanceradcliffept1"/>

Radcliffe is within the Manchester [[Larger Urban Zone]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/economic_unit/docs/wp13_towards_a_common_standard.pdf|title=Towards a Common Standard|page=29|format=PDF|publisher=Greater London Authority|accessdate=2008-10-05}}</ref> and within the Manchester [[Travel to Work Area]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/geography/ttwa.asp |title=Travel to Work Areas |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=2008-09-24}}</ref>

==Economy==
Radcliffe's first market was built by the [[Thomas Egerton, 2nd Earl of Wilton|Earl of Wilton]] and opened in 1851.<ref name="Farrerpp5667"/>  The town was home to twelve [[Co-op]] stores,<ref name="Hudsonp39">{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|p=39.}}</ref> the largest of which was on Stand Lane.  The four storey structure, built in 1877, had shops and offices on the ground floor, and a large area for public meetings on the second floor.<ref>{{Citation | title = Radcliffe Parish | url = http://www.mancuniensis.info/RadcliffeFPXX.htm | publisher = Salford Hundred | accessdate = 2008-10-26 }}</ref>  The building was truncated to two stories in June 1971, and eventually demolished.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sunderland|1995|p=48.}}</ref>  Two more Co-op stores were located on Bury Street<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|p=33.}}</ref> and Cross Lane.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|p=35.}}</ref>  The current market hall, built in 1937 on a different site to the old market, suffered a devastating fire in 1980<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|pp=47&ndash;49.}}</ref> but was later restored.  Radcliffe was once served by several banks including the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Bank]], the [[District Bank|Manchester and Liverpool District Bank]], the [[Union Bank of Manchester]], and [[Westminster Bank|Parr's Bank ltd]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Anon|1905|p=65.}}</ref>  Today both the [[Royal Bank of Scotland]] and [[Halifax (United Kingdom bank)|Halifax bank]] have branches in the town.<ref>{{Citation | title = RBS branch finder | url = http://www.rbs.co.uk/microsites/general/branch_locator/step1.asp | publisher = rbs.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-02-17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title = Halifax Bank branch finder | url = http://www.multimap.com/clients/browse.cgi?client=halifax&GridE=-2.32838&GridN=53.56258&lon=-2.32838&lat=53.56258&types=&db=GB&reclimit=15&place=Radcliffe%2C%20Manchester%2C%20Lancashire%2C%20England%2C%20M26%202&pc=&addr2=&client=halifax&addr3=radcliffe&scale=50000 | publisher = multimap.com | accessdate = 2009-02-17}}</ref>

[[Image:East lancs paper mill gate.jpg|thumb|The gate to the former East Lancashire Paper Mill, now demolished]]
Radcliffe has two weekly newspapers, the Radcliffe Times, based at the Bury Times offices, in [[Bury]],<ref>{{Citation | title = Radcliffe Times | url = http://www.mediauk.com/newspapers/342659/radcliffe-times | publisher = mediauk.com | accessdate = 2009-01-20 }}</ref> and the [[Salford]]-based The Advertiser, which also covers the neighbouring areas of [[Prestwich]] and [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Manchester local press | url = http://www.manchesteronline.co.uk/newspapers/prestwich.html | publisher = Manchesteronline.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-01-20 }}</ref>

The construction in the 1980s of the A665 Pilkington Way [[bypass (road)|Bypass]] relieved traffic congestion along the traditional route through the town, Blackburn Street. A new bridge across the Irwell was constructed for the road, and part of Blackburn Street was [[Car-free zone|pedestrianised]].  The road has attracted developments along former industrial land to the west of the town, including a large [[Asda]] supermarket, although it has exacerbated the decline of the retail outlets in the town centre.  The bypass has created problems for cyclists and pedestrians who appear reluctant to cross the road and visit the town centre.<ref name="reinventingradcliffep7"/><ref name="reinventingradcliffep8">{{Citation | title = Part 8 - SWOT Analysis | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/1FCF6DAC-E3C5-445D-BEB8-A55B05841394/0/Section8SWOTAnalysis.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | accessdate = 2008-12-10 }}</ref>  One solution presently under consideration would involve a partial reopening of the pedestrianised section of Blackburn Street to traffic.<ref name="reinventingradcliffep7">{{Citation | title = Part 7 - Access to the town centre | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/420A2FB8-77C0-4073-AFD9-AFA097019ADD/0/Section7AccesstothetowncentrePart1.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | accessdate = 2008-12-10 }}</ref>

[[Image:Timpsons shoes radcliffe greater manchester.jpg|thumb|Dale Street in 1966. Trade within the town's shopping centre has declined in recent years.]]
The closure of both the East Lancashire and Radcliffe Paper Mills, both of which employed thousands of people, has left a large gap in the town's local economy.<ref name="renaissanceradcliffept1"/>  Along with the decline of local industry the town's shopping centre has suffered a severe loss of trade and is now barely viable as a retail outlet.  The town's market hall compares poorly with the neighbouring [[Bury Market]].<ref name="reinventingradcliffep8"/>  Amongst other shops, the town's central shopping precinct retains a [[Boots the Chemist|Boots]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Store Details, Boots | url = http://www.boots.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/StoreLocator?lon=-2.325491&requiredAction=displayStoreDetails&bootsStoreId=4112&catalogId=11051&displayView=StoreDetailsDisplayView&inputLocation=Radcliffe,%20Manchester,%20Lancashire,%20England,%20M26%202&langId=-1&lat=53.55876&storeId=10052&inputPostcode= | publisher = www.boots.com | accessdate = 2008-12-21}}</ref>  A [[Dunelm Mill]] store now occupies the former site of the town's Asda supermarket.<ref>{{Citation | title = Store Locater | url = http://www.dunelm-mill.com/pages/storelocator/choosestore.asp | publisher = www.dunelm-mill.com | accessdate = 2008-12-21 }}</ref>

"Re-inventing Radcliffe" is the name given on a report of a proposed improvement scheme.  The report envisages several initiatives, and includes the creation of new housing both to the north and south of the town.  Existing industry to the west of the town and along Milltown Street would be retained and improved, along with sections of the former Radcliffe Paper Mill and Pioneer Mill.  The market would be redeveloped along with the [[Kwik Save]] site and bus station, and the town could become a centre for the arts.  To improve transport links, new crossings of the Irwell and canal are proposed, along with a new school to replace the two existing [[secondary school]]s.  Finally, the report suggests improving the image of Radcliffe within the Bury area.<ref name="Re-inventingRadcliffeReport"/>

[[Image:Radcliffe precinct greater manchester.jpg|thumb|600px|center|A panorama of Radcliffe's main shopping area, Radcliffe Precinct]]
"Newlands" is a regeneration programme run by the [[Forestry Commission]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Newlands | url = http://www.forestry.gov.uk/newlands | publisher = The Forestry Commission | accessdate = 2008-11-21 }}</ref>  One site under consideration for regeneration is the former waste tip of Radcliffe E'es.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bury.gov.uk/Environment/Planning/PlanningProjects/CountrysideAndWildlife/NewlandsRFRE.htm |title=Newlands / Rhodes Farm and Radcliffe Ees |publisher=Bury.gov.uk}} Retrieved on 23&nbsp;December 2008.</ref>

