In 1921 2,394&nbsp;men and 3,680&nbsp;women were employed in the textile industry.<ref name="radcliffe1921">{{Citation | title = Radcliffe MB/UD: Persons of Working Age by Sex and 1921 Occupational Order  | url = http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_IND&data_cube=N_OCC_ORD1921&u_id=10109164&c_id=10001043&add=Y | publisher = A Vision of Britain through Time, Standardised Industry data | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref>  By 1951 these figures had fallen respectively to 981&nbsp;and&nbsp;1,852.<ref name="radcliffe1951">{{Citation | title = Radcliffe MB/UD: Persons of Working Age by Sex and 1951 Occupational Order  | url = http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_IND&data_cube=N_OCC_ORD1951&u_id=10109164&c_id=10001043&add=Y | publisher = A Vision of Britain through Time, Standardised Industry data | accessdate = 2008-10-29}}</ref>  A more drastic fall is evident in the numbers of people employed in the mining and quarrying industries; in 1921 591&nbsp;people were employed in both,<ref name="radcliffe1921"/> but in 1951 this had dropped to only&nbsp;57,<ref name="radcliffe1951"/> reflecting the number of mines in and around Radcliffe that had by that time been completely exhausted.<ref name="Sunderlandpp8385"/>

By 2001, from a working population of 15,972&nbsp;between the ages of 16<U+2013>74 only six&nbsp;people were employed in mining. 3,011&nbsp;people were employed in manufacturing, 103&nbsp;in [[Public utility|public utilities]], and 985&nbsp;in construction.  3,371&nbsp;people worked in wholesale and retailing; repair of motor vehicles, 682&nbsp;in hotels and catering, and 1,185&nbsp;in transport; storage and communication. 642&nbsp;people worked in [[Financial intermediary|financial intermediation]], 1,711&nbsp;in real estate, 694&nbsp;in [[public administration]] and defence, 987&nbsp;in education, 1,876&nbsp;in health and social work, and 657&nbsp;in other work.<ref>{{Citation | title = KS11a Industry of employment <U+2013> all people: Census 2001, Key Statistics for urban areas | url = http://www.statistics.gov.uk/statbase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8306&More=Y | date = 2005-02-07 | publisher = Statistics.gov.uk | accessdate = 2008-12-07 }}</ref>

==Landmarks==
[[Image:Radcliffe cenotaph.jpg|thumb|upright|Radcliffe Cenotaph]]
[[Radcliffe Tower]] is all that remains of an early 15th century stone-built [[manor house]].<ref name="Pastscape">{{Citation |title=Radcliffe Tower |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=44210 |publisher=Pastscape.org.uk |accessdate=2008-01-05}}</ref>  The structure is a [[Grade I listed buildings in Greater Manchester|Grade I listed building]] and protected as a [[Scheduled Monument]].<ref name="Pastscape"/><ref name="Images of England">{{Citation|title=Radcliffe Tower |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=210639 |publisher=Images of England|accessdate=2008-01-05}}</ref>  The construction of a nearby [[tithe barn]] is not documented, but it was probably built between 1600 and 1720.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=44213&sort=1&type=&class1=None&period=None&county=Greater%20Manchester&place=Radcliffe&yearfrom=ALL&yearto=ALL&recordsperpage=5&source=text&nmr=&defra=&p=0 |publisher=Pastscape.com |title=Tithe barn |accessdate=2008-12-12}}</ref> It was used for storage of the local [[tithe]]s (a tenth of a farm's produce).<ref>{{Harvnb|Darvill|2003|p=433.}}</ref>  Along with Radcliffe Tower, the [[Parish Church of St Mary, Radcliffe|Parish Church of St Mary]] is a Grade I listed building.<ref name="Stmarylisted">{{Citation|title=Church of St Mary and St Bartholomew|url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=210617|publisher=Images of England|accessdate=2007-12-23}}</ref>  The town also has two [[Listed building|Grade II* listed building]]s; Dearden Fold Farmhouse, completed during the 16th century,<ref>{{Citation|title=Dearden Fold Farmhouse |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=210607 |publisher=Images of England |accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> and Radcliffe Cenotaph, built in 1922 to commemorate the First World War.<ref>{{Citation|title=Radcliffe Cenotaph |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/Details/Default.aspx?id=210777 |publisher=Images of England |accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref>  [[Outwood Viaduct]], and Radcliffe's most visible landmark, St Thomas' Church, are Grade II listed buildings.<ref>{{Citation | title = What to do or visit: Radcliffe | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/VisitorGuidesAndMaps/Radcliffe/Radcliffe_visit.htm | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | accessdate = 2008-10-28 }}</ref>  St Thomas' took nine years to complete. The first stone was laid by [[Viscount Grey de Wilton]] (grandson of the Countess Grosvenor) on 21 July 1862, and it was [[Consecration|consecrated]] in 1864 by the first [[Bishop of Manchester]], [[James Prince Lee]].  Construction of the tower began in 1870<ref>{{Harvnb|Gooderson|1985|p=14.}}</ref> and the building was completed in 1871.  The building cost <U+00A3>7,273,<ref name="Goodersonp8"/> (<U+00A3>{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|7273|1871|r=-4}}|0}} today){{Inflation-fn|UK}} and the tower cost <U+00A3>1,800 (<U+00A3>{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|1800|1871|r=-4}}|0}} today).{{Inflation-fn|UK}} The first vicar was the Reverend Robert Fletcher.

Radcliffe's first public ornament was a drinking fountain located at the bottom of Radcliffe New Road.  It was presented to the town by a Mrs Noah Rostron in memory of her husband, and erected in August 1896.<ref>{{Citation | title = Radcliffe Historical Almanack | last = Swinburne | first = Rev. Stanley | publisher = unknown | date = unknown | location = Bury Library, Local Studies | page = 4 }}</ref>  The fountain no longer exists at this location.

Built in 1911 the [[town hall]] was on the junction of Water Street and Spring Lane.<ref name="Hudsonp110"/>  For many years after the town lost its [[urban district]] status, the building was unoccupied.  It was converted to private accommodation in 1999.<ref>{{Citation | title = Radcliffe Town Hall | url = http://www.byphl.co.uk/old_radcliffe_town_h.html | publisher = The Housing Link | year = 2003 | accessdate = 2007-11-13}}</ref>

==Transport==
The Manchester to Blackburn [[packhorse]] route passed through the town (hence the name Blackburn Street).  The bridge across the Irwell was likely first erected during the late Medieval period at the site of a ford.  An [[Act of Parliament]] in 1754 authorised the first turnpike through the hamlet of Radcliffe Bridge,<ref name="Wellspp102103">{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|pp=102&ndash;103.}}</ref> and included Manchester to Bury via [[Crumpsall]], and from [[Prestwich]] to Radcliffe.  An Act of 1821 created a turnpike from Bury to Radcliffe, [[Stoneclough]] and [[Bolton]].  An Act of 1836 created a turnpike from Starling Lane to [[Ainsworth, Greater Manchester|Ainsworth]], and Radcliffe to Bury and Manchester Road (near Fletcher Fold).  A turnpike from Whitefield to Radcliffe Bridge via Stand Lane was created in 1857 with [[toll house]]s at [[Besses o' th' Barn]], Stand Lane, the junction of Dumers Lane and Manchester Road, on Bolton Road near Countess Lane, and on Radcliffe Moor Road at Bradley Fold.  Radcliffe New Road was created in an Act of 1860 which enabled the construction of a toll road between Radcliffe and Whitefield.<ref name="Sunderlandp53">{{Harvnb|Sunderland|1995|p=53.}}</ref>  To prevent damage to the road surfaces, weighing machines were used at various strategic positions including at the bridge end of Dumers Lane, at Sandiford turning, and on Ainsworth Road.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicholls|1900|pp=108, 111.}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title = Records of Prestwich, Bury and Radcliffe Turnpike Trust | url = http://archives.bury.gov.uk/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=NaviTreeX.tcl&dsqField=RefNo&dsqItem=APT#HERE | publisher = Bury Archives Catalogue | location = Bury Archives Service, Moss Street, Bury | accessdate = 2008-10-28}}</ref>

[[Image:1911 radcliffe manchester.png|left|thumb|This 1911 map demonstrates the significant railway infrastructure through the town]]
During the [[Industrial Revolution]], as local [[Cottage_industry#Cottage_industry|cottage industries]] were gradually supplanted by the [[factory system]] the roads became inadequate for use.  A convoy of horse-drawn lorries carrying salt between Bealey's Bleach Works and [[Northwich]] would take up to two weeks to make a return journey.<ref name="Sunderlandp53"/>  These problems gave rise to the construction of the [[Manchester, Bolton & Bury Canal]], which reached the town in 1796 and which was navigable throughout in 1808.  For 38&nbsp;years the canal was the town's main route for trade and transport, with a [[wharf]] near Hampson Street.  The proprietors later converted into a railway company and built a line between [[Salford]] and [[Bolton]], which opened in 1838.  A branch from this line was to have been built to [[Bury]], along the line of the canal, but due to technical constraints this did not happen.<ref name="Wellsp3">{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=3.}}</ref>  Radcliffe's closest railway connection therefore several miles distant at [[Kearsley railway station|Stoneclough]].<ref name="Ordnancesurvey"/>

The opening of the [[Manchester, Bury and Rossendale Railway]] (later known as the [[East Lancashire Railway 1844<U+2013>1859|East Lancashire Railway]] (ELR)) in 1846<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=4.}}</ref> brought the town a direct connection to Manchester and [[Bury Bolton Street railway station|Bury]].  Two stations served the town, [[Radcliffe Bridge railway station|Radcliffe Bridge station]], and [[Withins Lane railway station|Withins Lane station]] (although this closed in 1851 after only a few years of operation).  [[Ringley Road railway station|Ringley Road station]] was located to the south of the parish, close to the civil parish of Pilkington.  The line crossed the Irwell over [[Outwood Viaduct]], an impressive structure which remains to this day.<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|pp=109&ndash;115.}}</ref>

The [[Liverpool and Bury Railway]] (L&BR) opened on 28 November 1848, with a station to the north of the town, called [[Black Lane railway station (Radcliffe)|Black Lane station]]. On 18 July 1872 the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] (L&YR), which had amalgamated with the ELR some years previously, gained an Act of Parliament to construct a railway between Manchester and Bury, via [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]] and [[Prestwich]].  This opened in 1879 with a new station, known as [[Radcliffe Metrolink station|Radcliffe New Station]],<ref>From 1933 this station was renamed "Radcliffe Central"</ref> with a link to the L&BR line at Bradley Fold (near the present day Chatsworth Road), and a new station along Ainsworth Road, [[Ainsworth Road Halt railway station|Ainsworth Road Halt]]. The new L&YR route joined the existing ELR route near Withins Lane (North Junction), whereon they shared the connection to Bury.  The L&YR gained a further Act of 1877 to construct a link between North Junction and Coney Green Farm (West Junction). The LY&R line was electrified in 1916 for which a substation was constructed, between the canal and the West Fork.<ref name="Wellspp102103"/>

The town also had an extensive [[Tram#Electric_.28trolley_cars.29|tram]] network.  The first tram ran from Black Lane (latterly Ainsworth Road) in 1905, with a terminus next to St Andrew's Church on Black Lane Bridge.  In 1907 a branch was built to connect to the Bury to Bolton part of the network.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sunderland|1995|p=43.}}</ref>  A large bus station is located between Dale Street and the river.<ref name="GMPTEradcliffe">{{Citation | title = Radcliffe Bus Station | url = http://www.gmpte.com/destination/Radcliffe.pdf | publisher = GMPTE | date = 2008-06-09 | accessdate = 2009-01-01 | format = PDF}}</ref>  Officially abandoned in 1961, the canal is currently undergoing restoration on the [[Salford]] arm,<ref name=fullsteam>{{Citation | title = Full Steam Ahead For Canal Restoration In Salford | publisher = British Waterways | url = http://www.britishwaterways.co.uk/newsroom/all-press-releases/display/id/1738 | accessdate=2008-06-27}}</ref> although a rebuilt bridge along Water Street presents a barrier to its full restoration.<ref>{{Citation | title = History of the Waterway - Restoration | url = http://www.mbbcs.org.uk/history/restoration.htm | publisher = Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Society | accessdate = 2008-12-12 }}</ref>

[[Image:Metrolink at Dolly Molly.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Manchester Metrolink]] tram leaves Radcliffe, part of Greater Manchester's light rail public transport system]]
Public transport in Radcliffe is now coordinated by the [[Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive]] (GMPTE), a county-wide public body with direct operational responsibilities such as supporting (and in some cases running) local bus services, and managing integrated ticketing in Greater Manchester.<ref name="GMPTEradcliffe"/>

The town is now served only by a single light rail system and regular bus services.<ref name="GMPTEradcliffe"/>  The [[Manchester Metrolink|Metrolink]] opened on 6 April 1992 along the L&YR line between Manchester and Bury.<ref>{{Harvnb|Simpson|1994|p=57.}}</ref>  Trams leave from the town's station every six minutes between 7:15 am and 6:30 pm, and every 12&nbsp;minutes at other times of the day.<ref>{{Citation | title = Tram Times | publisher = Metrolink | url = http://www.metrolink.co.uk/tramtimes/index.asp | accessdate = 2009-01-01}}</ref>  Radcliffe Bridge station closed on 5 July 1958,<ref>{{Harvnb|Wells|1995|p=114.}}</ref> and has since been replaced by the path of the A665 Pilkington Way (the new road has been built below the level of the old station).<ref name="OSradcliffe"/>  The path of the ELR line is still quite visible from aerial photography, with [[Outwood Viaduct]] fully restored,<ref>{{Citation | title = Outwood Viaduct Restoration | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/Environment/Planning/PlanningProjects/PastProjects/OutwoodVia.htm | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | accessdate = 2008-12-12 }}</ref> and the route of the line southwest of the town converted for use as a nature trail forming part of the [[Irwell Sculpture Trail]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Bury's Irwell Sculpture Trail | url = http://www.irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk/IST_sculpture_leaflet.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-01-01 }}</ref>

==Education==
{{seealso|List of schools in Bury}}
[[Image:Radcliffe technical school 1896 greater manchester.jpg|thumb|upright|The former entrance to Radcliffe Technical School. The building is now used by the local council as office space.]]
One of the earliest schools in the parish was the Close Wesleyan Day School, a [[Dame school]] opened around 1840.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicholls|1900|p=30.}}</ref>  St Thomas's day school was opened on 4 March 1861, and housed over 500&nbsp;children.  Due to overcrowding and the risk of subsidence caused by local mining activity, the school was rebuilt on a new site along School Street, provided by the [[Thomas Egerton, 2nd Earl of Wilton|Earl of Wilton]].  It was opened in October 1877 by Lady Wilton.  On the opposite side of the town St John's school started life in 1860 as an institute along Irwell Street, and by 1864 contained 120&nbsp;children.  The buildings were enlarged in 1869.  In 1897 eight teachers and a monitor taught 358&nbsp;children.  In 1899 the school leaving age was twelve, and many of the senior class were "half-timers" who would spend half the day at school, and the other half at work.  This system was abolished in 1919.  Regular epidemics of [[scarlet fever]], [[chicken pox]], [[mumps]], and especially [[measles]], meant that in 1897 and 1903 the school was temporarily closed.<ref>{{Harvnb|Gooderson|1985|pp=62&ndash;63.}}</ref>  St John's school and the nearby Church were demolished in the 1970s.<ref name="StThomasHistory"/>  Radcliffe also had a Technical school on Whittaker Street.  Formally opened by Lord Stanley on 7 November 1896, it adjoined the public baths on Whittaker Street.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicholls|1900|p=255.}}</ref> The building is now used as council offices.<ref>{{Citation | title = Buildings in Radcliffe | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/CouncilGovernmentAndDemocracy/Councils/ContactsConsultationAndFeedback/ContactingCouncilOfficials/BuildingsRadcliffe.htm | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | accessdate = 2008-12-12}}</ref>

Radcliffe County Secondary School was founded in 1933<ref>{{Citation | title = Radcliffe High School Prospectus | location = Bury Library, Local Studies, r25.21(P) | year = 1992 }}</ref> on the former Peel Park Ground near School Street, but Radcliffe's first secondary school (apart from an endowed [[grammar school]] in nearby Stand) was held at the New Jerusalem schoolroom from the early 1860s.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicholls|1900|p=306.}}</ref>  Radcliffe East, latterly known as Coney Green County Comprehensive School, was built in 1975 on the site of the former railway goods yard alongside Radcliffe East Fork.  Part of the school, known as "Phase One", opened in September 1975, with 150&nbsp;first-year pupils, and 70&nbsp;second-year pupils (from Radcliffe County Secondary School).  The remainder, known as "Phase Two", opened two years later.<ref>{{Citation | title = School will be a vital part of the community | last = Waller | first = Andrew | publisher = ''Radcliffe Times'' | date = 1975-06-12 | page = 11 }}</ref>

Radcliffe has ten primary schools, and one secondary school which is spread across two sites.  Presently, these two secondary school sites have been renamed Radcliffe Riverside East Campus (Coney Green) and Radcliffe Riverside West Campus (Radcliffe High).  The lower school students in years&nbsp;7<U+2013>9 study at the Coney Green building, while the upper school students between years&nbsp;10<U+2013>11 study in the Radcliffe High building.  A new school is proposed to replace Coney Green High School and Radcliffe High School,<ref name="Re-inventingRadcliffeReport">{{Citation | title = Re-inventing Radcliffe Report | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/Business/EconomicDevelopment/EconomicRegeneration/RadcliffeRegenerationRe-inventingRadcliffe.htm | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | date = September 2003 | accessdate = 2008-10-26}}</ref> however recent developments have delayed construction of the new school.<ref>{{Citation | title = Riverside row rages on | url = http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/3823162.Riverside_row_rages_on/ | publisher = ''Bury Times'' | date = 2008-11-06 | accessdate = 2008-11-22 }}</ref>

==Religious sites==
[[Image:Radcliffe Parish Church.jpg|thumb|Parish Church of St Mary, Radcliffe]]
In [[Romano-British culture|Romano<U+2013>British]] times, Radcliffe was in the [[Diocese of York]]; in [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] times in the Diocese of [[Lindesfarne]], then of York; in [[Normans|Norman]] times in the Diocese of [[Lichfield]]; after 1540 in the Diocese of [[Chester]] and since 1847 in the [[Anglican Diocese of Manchester|Diocese of Manchester]].<ref>{{Citation |title=Radcliffe Parish Church History |publisher=Radcliffe Parish Church |url=http://radcliffeparishchurch.org.uk/history.htm |accessdate=2008-11-16}}</ref>

Based on the subdivisions of the dioceses, before 1535<ref>The exact date is unknown.</ref> Radcliffe ancient parish was in Manchester and Blackburn [[Rural Dean|Rural Deanery]].  Between this date and 1850 the ancient parish was placed in Manchester Rural Deanery.  From 1850<U+2013>1851 it was placed in Bury Rural Deanery; from 1851<U+2013>1872, it was in Prestwich Rural Deanery; from 1872<U+2013>1912, it was placed in Prestwich and Middleton Rural Deanery, and since 1872 it has been in Radcliffe and Prestwich Rural Deanery.<ref name=youngsp195-196>{{Harvnb|Youngs|1991|pp=195&ndash;196}}</ref>

===Church of England===
Radcliffe was an ancient parish which in its early history had duties which combined both ecclesiastical and civil matters.  In 1821 Radcliffe St. Thomas [[ecclesiastical parish]] was created from the ancient parish, and it was re-founded in 1839.  In 1873 further parts of the ancient parish were taken to form Bury St. Peters ecclesiastical parish.  In 1878 parts of the ancient parish as well as part of Radcliffe St. Thomas were taken to form Radcliffe St. Andrew, Black Lane ecclesiastical parish.<ref name=youngsp195-196/>  The [[Parish Church of St Mary, Radcliffe|Parish Church of St Mary]] was built during the 14th century, and the tower added in the 15th century.  In 1966 it was designated a [[Grade I]] [[listed building]] by [[English Heritage]] under its former name of the Church of St Mary and St Bartholomew.<ref name="Stmarylisted"/>  In 1991 some local parishes were merged, and the church adopted its present name.<ref>{{Citation |title=Radcliffe Parish Church |publisher=Radcliffe Parish Church |url=http://www.radcliffeparishchurch.org.uk/index.htm |accessdate=2008-01-14}}</ref>

[[Image:Stand Lane Radcliffe looking north 1902.jpg|thumb|The many chimneys visible in this 1902 image of the town give an indication as to the degree of industrialisation. The Church of St John is visible here.]]
Radcliffe is also served by the Parish of St Thomas and St John.  St Thomas' is visible on the horizon for many miles. The original church was built in 1819 by Countess Grosvenor<ref name="Goodersonp8">{{Harvnb|Gooderson|1985|p=8.}}</ref> and is visible above in the image of Radcliffe Bridge.  The building was later considered too small, and in 1862 was demolished and replaced with the present structure (see landmarks).  The Church of St John was consecrated on 19 February 1866 at the bottom of Radcliffe New Road.  Built at a cost of about <U+00A3>4,000 (<U+00A3>{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|4000|1866|r=-4}}|0}} today){{Inflation-fn|UK}} the site was donated to the church by the [[Earl of Derby]], who in 1897 also made a grant of land for the site of the Mission Church at Chapelfield.<ref>{{Harvnb|Anon|1905|p=20.}}</ref>  The parishes of St John and St Philip were merged with St Thomas' in 1975<U+2013>1976.<ref>Both these churches were later demolished</ref><ref name="StThomasHistory">{{Citation | title = History of St Thomas' Church | url = http://www.st-thomas-radcliffe.org/history.html | publisher = St Thomas and St John | accessdate = 2008-10-28 }}</ref>  Radcliffe is also home to the Church of St Andrew on Ainsworth road, which was consecrated in 1877.<ref>{{Harvnb|Anon|1905|p=21.}}</ref>

===Other faiths===
Radcliffe was also home to many smaller churches.  The main [[Roman Catholic]] church, St. Mary & St. Philip Neri, on Spring Lane, was built in 1894.<ref>{{Citation | title = Parish History | url = http://www.radcliffecatholic.org/ourhistory.htm | publisher = www.radcliffecatholic.org | accessdate = 2008-10-26 }}</ref>  Other churches included Stand Independent, a [[Quakers|Quaker]] church on Foundry Street, Water Lane [[Congregational]], and several [[Wesleyan Church|Wesleyan churches]], including one on Bridgefield Street, which in March 2008 was destroyed by fire.<ref>{{Citation | title = Inquiry as church wrecked by fire | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/7306393.stm | publisher = BBC News | date = 2008-03-20 | accessdate = 2008-11-16 }}</ref>  The church was built in 1892.<ref>{{Citation | title = Loss and Hope in Radcliffe | url = http://www.methodist.org.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=opentoworld.content&cmid=2218 | publisher = The Methodist Church of Great Britain | accessdate = 2008-11-16 }}</ref>  The [[United Reformed Church]] has two congregations within the town, one on Lord Street, and the other on Stand Lane.  The church was originally formed from a Congregational school in 1848.<ref>{{Citation | title = Radcliffe and Stand United Reformed Churches | url = http://www.radcliffeurc.org.uk/ | publisher = Radcliffe United Reformed Church | accessdate = 2008-11-16 }}</ref>  A [[Methodist New Connexion]] church has existed along Smyrna Street since 1844.<ref>{{Harvnb|Anon|1905|pp=23&ndash;47.}}</ref>  Other faiths are also catered for, with a [[mosque]] on Bridgefield Street,<ref>{{Citation | title = Masjid Noor and Islamic Education Centre | url = http://mosques.muslimsinbritain.org/show-mosque.php?id=2095 | publisher = UK Mosque Searcher | accessdate = 2008-12-01}}</ref> and a centre for [[Swedenborgianism]] on Radcliffe New Road.<ref>{{Citation | title = Theological and Religious Studies Collection Directory | url = http://www.newman.ac.uk/abtapl/database/LibraryPage246.html | publisher = Assoc. of British Theological and Philosophical Libraries | accessdate = 2008-12-01}}</ref>

==Sports==
Radcliffe has a rich history of sport, including [[association football|football]], [[rugby league|rugby]], cricket and swimming, but entertainment in Radcliffe once included [[bear-baiting]], [[bull-baiting]], and [[Cockfight|cock-fighting]].  Cock fights were prevalent in the town and took place in local "hush-shops", generally viewed by invitation only.  Bull and bear baiting was held in the Radcliffe Bridge area of the parish.  In Nicholls' ''History and Traditions of Radcliffe'' (1900) the author describes the contents of the diary of a Lord Kenyon, who wrote "W.M. Robt. James, and Thomas Radcliffe, were fined for causing a Bayre to be bayted upon Saturday being the 18th of March 1587<U+2013>8, at the Bull-Ringe neere the conduite in Manchester."<ref name="Nicholls208">{{Harvnb|Nicholls|pp=207&ndash;208.}}</ref>  Trained dogs were used to attack a bull, which was donated by the Earl of Wilton.  Such entertainment would take place where the bridge now stands, along the banks of the river near the ford.  Such spectacles were eventually outlawed by Act of Parliament, and the last bull bait in the town was held on 26&nbsp;September 1838.  Horse racing replaced the sport the following year, with a course alongside the river.  During the first year of racing the main spectator stand collapsed, injuring many spectators.  In 1876 events were moved to a new course<ref name="Nicholls208"/> approximately one mile in circumference<ref>{{Harvnb|Langley|1854|p=248.}}</ref> at Radcliffe Moor, upon which site the town's cricket club now stands.<ref name="Nicholls208"/>

The town is home to [[Central Lancashire Cricket League]] side [[Radcliffe Cricket Club]].  For many years [[Sir Frank Worrell]] played the club,<ref name="Hudsonpp126127"/> and a street near the cricket ground was named in his honour.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IcxYwq0sB_8C |title=Cricket Nurseries of Colonial Barbados, The Elite Schools, 1865<U+2013>1966 | page = 126 | publisher=Press University of the West Indies | accessdate = 2007-10-29}}</ref>  Sir [[Garfield Sobers]] joined the club in 1958 at the age of&nbsp;21.<ref name="Hudsonpp126127">{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|pp=126&ndash;127.}}</ref>  The town also has a [[Football team]], [[Radcliffe Borough F.C.|Radcliffe Borough]].  Famous players include [[Paul Gascoigne]]<ref>{{Citation | title = Borough make their mark on Gascoigne | url = http://archive.lancashireeveningtelegraph.co.uk/2004/7/26/477776.html | publisher = ''Bolton Evening News'' | date = 2004-07-24 | accessdate = 2008-11-03}}</ref> and [[Matt Derbyshire]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Matt Derbyshire: 'I didn't care about the financial side. It was because I supported Rovers as a kid, and was brought up in Blackburn' | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/matt-derbyshire-i-didnt-care-about-the-financial-side-it-was-because-i-supported-rovers-as-a-kid-and-was-brought-up-in-blackburn-444588.html | publisher = ''The Independent'' | date = 2007-04-14 | accessdate = 2008-11-03}}</ref>

==Public services==
===History===
The [[Rivers Pollution Prevention Act 1876]] posed a problem for the local authorities; disposal of sewage was generally an expensive proposition, and efforts to resolve the practical problems involved were often unsatisfactory.  After initial experiments, in 1894 contracts were let for work.  Chairman of the Local Board Samuel Walker Esq cut the first sod on 23 April 1894, and the works were completed in the following year.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicholls|1900|pp=242&ndash;243.}}</ref>

The town was provided with electricity by a coal-fired power station along the south bank of the river, to the west of the town.  Authorised by the Radcliffe Electric Lighting Order of 1894, and inaugurated on 5 October 1904,<ref>{{Harvnb|Borough of Radcliffe|1935|p=19.}}</ref> [[Radcliffe Power Station]] was opened by the [[Frederick Stanley, 16th Earl of Derby|Earl of Derby]] on 9 October 1905.<ref name=Times>{{Citation | title = Lancashire Electric Light and Power | publisher = ''[[The Times]] newspaper'' | page=22 | date = 1922-02-19}}</ref>  It originally had two 1,500&nbsp;kW turbo sets made by [[British Thomson-Houston]], and was the first power station in the country to transmit electricity over bare electrical conductors.<ref>{{Harvnb|Frost|1993|p=}}</ref>

In 1921 the Radcliffe and Little Lever Joint Gas Board purchased the Radcliffe & Pilkington Gas Company.  Constituted in 1921 by an Act of Parliament, the board consisted of six members of the Radcliffe Council and one member of the Little Lever Council.  The area supplied included all the districts of Radcliffe and Little Lever, and also Prestwich, Whitefield, Unsworth, Outwood, and Ainsworth.  In 1935 the company supplied {{convert|263000000|cuft|m3}} of gas to 16,748&nbsp;consumers, and provided gas for public street lighting.  Water supplies were provided both by upland [[Drainage divide|watersheds]] and by the Bury & District Joint Water Board, of which Radcliffe was a constituent authority.<ref>{{Harvnb|Borough of Radcliffe|1935|p=20.}}</ref>

By 1935 a fire brigade and ambulances were available to protect the town during emergencies.  The [[Fire alarm box|Gamewell]] system of fire alarms was used and consisted of 16&nbsp;alarm boxes spread throughout the district.  Three motor ambulances and a motorised utility van were kept at the [[fire station]], operated by permanent staff.<ref>{{Harvnb|Borough of Radcliffe|1935|p=25.}}</ref>

===Modern services===
The [[North West Ambulance Service]] provides emergency patient transport, and the [[Fire service in the United Kingdom|statutory emergency fire and rescue service]] is now provided by the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/bury.aspx|publisher=manchesterfire.gov.uk|author=[[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]]|accessdate=2008-10-30|title=My area: Bury}}</ref>

[[Home Office]] policing in Radcliffe is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Police]]. The force's "(N) Division" has a police station in Radcliffe, along Railway Street.  [[Waste management]] is coordinated by the [[local authority]] via the [[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.gmwda.gov.uk/|title=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority (GMWDA)|publisher=gmwda.gov.uk|author=[[Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority]]|year=2008|accessdate=2008-02-08}}</ref> Radcliffe's [[Distribution Network Operator]] for electricity is [[United Utilities]].<ref name="UU">{{Citation|url=http://www.unitedutilities.com/Bury.htm|title=Bury|publisher=unitedutilities.com|author=[[United Utilities]]|date=2007-04-06|accessdate=2008-10-30}}</ref>

== Notable people ==
Born in Radcliffe, [[Private (rank)|Private]] First World War veteran [[James Hutchinson (VC)|James Hutchinson]] was a recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]].<ref>{{Citation | title = 'Back to school' for war hero | url = http://archive.lancashireeveningtelegraph.co.uk/2000/11/17/705533.html | publisher = archive.lancashireeveningtelegraph.co.uk | date = 2000-11-17 | accessdate = 2009-01-01 }}</ref>  Radcliffe was also the birthplace of Canadian author [[Donald Jack]]<ref>{{Citation | title = Three cheers for a funny fellow | url = http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/TPStory/LAC/20030612/OBJACK/ | date = 2003-06-12 | last = Cooper | first = Carol | publisher = Globeandmail.com | accessdate = 2009-01-19}}</ref> and also the home of Olympic medal winning cyclist [[Harry Hill (cyclist)|Harry Hill]] who took bronze at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Harry checks progress on his path | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/PressReleases/PressRelease.htm?PRID={00f8bd24-7f13-4cbf-aa34-3854dfdd78c1} | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | date = 2006-06-19 | accessdate = 2009-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | title= Goodbye to a true cycling superstar | url = http://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/radcliffenews/4103768.Goodbye_to_a_true_cycling_superstar/ | date = 2009-02-05 | publisher = burytimes.co.uk | accessdate = 2009-02-09 }}</ref>  [[Nellie Halstead]] was a swimmer who represented Britain in both the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] and [[1936 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|pp=117&ndash;128.}}</ref>  Radcliffe was also the birthplace of film director [[Danny Boyle]]<ref>{{Citation | title = Danny Boyle | url = http://movies.nytimes.com/person/188724/Danny-Boyle/biography | publisher = ''New York Times'' | accessdate = 2008-10-29 }}</ref> and the late [[snooker]] player, [[John Spencer (snooker player)|John Spencer]].<ref>{{Citation | title = John Spencer | last = Baxter | first = Trevor | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-spencer-407717.html | date = 2006-07-13 | publisher = ''The Independent'' | accessdate = 2008-12-12 }}</ref>

== Culture ==
[[Image:Radcliffe greater manchester carnival 2.jpg|thumb|right|A contemporary view of Radcliffe's annual traditional English [[Carnival#England|Carnival]]]]
Radcliffe's wealth as a mill town gave rise to many outlets for the entertainment of its population.  These included cinemas and [[public house]]s.  Several cinemas were built in the town, including the Picturedrome in Water Street,<ref name="Hudsonp39"/> and an Odeon cinema, built in 1937 along Dale Street.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|pp=108&ndash;109.}}</ref>  Whittaker Street [[Public bathing|public baths]] were built in 1898 and demolished in 1971.<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|p=46.}}</ref>  Radcliffe Pool now provides swimming facilities for the local population.  A public library was opened in 1907<ref>{{Harvnb|Hudson|2001|p=51.}}</ref> on a site donated by [[Andrew Carnegie]], who also contributed <U+00A3>5,000 (<U+00A3>{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|5000|1907|r=-4}}|0}} today){{Inflation-fn|UK}} towards the cost of the building.  Two branch libraries were opened in Ainsworth between 1933 and 1935.<ref name="boroughradcliffep26">{{Harvnb|Borough of Radcliffe|1935|p=26.}}</ref>  A museum was located in the upper rooms of Close House before it was demolished in March 1969.<ref>{{Citation | title = Close Park, History | url = http://www.bury.gov.uk/LeisureAndCulture/ParksAndRecreation/UrbanParks/ClosePark/History.htm | publisher = Bury Metropolitan Borough Council | accessdate = 2008-12-12}}</ref>

Radcliffe Brass Band has performed in the town since 1914, when it accompanied one of the [[Whit_Friday#Whit_walks|Whit Walks]] that used to take place on [[Whit Friday]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Band Love Being Back in Town | url = http://www.burytimes.co.uk/search/3702963.Band_love_being_back_in_town/ | date = 2008-09-27 | publisher = ''Bury Times'' | accessdate = 2008-11-04 }}</ref>  Popular as these were, support later dwindled to a point where they were abandoned around 1977.<ref>{{Harvnb|Sunderland|1995|p=98.}}</ref>  [[Rushcart]] processions were once popular, held on the first Saturday of September, finishing on the following Sunday at the Parish Church.<ref>{{Harvnb|Nicholls|1900|p=210.}}</ref>

The town has two parks, Coronation Park near Radcliffe Bridge, and Close Park near Radcliffe Tower.  Much of the land for Coronation Park was in 1900 donated by the Earl of Derby.  Close House and the grounds around it were formerly the home of the Bealey family, and were donated by the [[Bleachers' Association]].<ref name="boroughradcliffep26"/>  The town is also along the route of the [[Irwell Sculpture Trail]].<ref>{{Citation | title = Bury's Irwell Sculpture Trail | url = http://www.irwellsculpturetrail.co.uk/IST_sculpture_leaflet.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = Bury Tourist Information Centre | accessdate = 2008-12-12 }}</ref>

